# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dauricine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Abbreviated "phen", or sometimes "o-phen" for ortho-phenanthroline, it is used as a ligand in coordination chemistry, forming strong complexes with most metal ions.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Phenanthroline can be prepared by two successive Skraup reactions of glycerol with *o*-phenylenediamine, catalyzed by sulfuric acid, and an oxidizing agent, traditionally aqueous arsenic acid or nitrobenzene.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Dehydration of glycerol gives acrolein which condenses with the amine followed by a cyclization.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Oxidation of 1,10-phenanthroline with a mixture of nitric and sulfuric acids gives 1,10-phenanthroline-5,6-dione.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] 1,10-Phenanthroline forms many coordination complexes.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] One example is the iron complex called ferroin.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Alkyllithium reagents form deeply colored derivatives with phenanthroline.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] The alkyllithium content of solutions can be determined by treatment of such reagents with small amounts of phenanthroline (ca.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] 1 mg) followed by titration with alcohols to a colourless endpoint.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Grignard reagents may be similarly titrated.
[src:dauricine/1-10-phenanthroline] Phenanthroline is used in biochemical and pharmacological research as an inhibitor of the deubiquitination enzyme Rpn11.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] In ROS biology, superoxide was identified as the major reactive oxygen species induced by TPA/PMA but not by ionomycin in mouse macrophages.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] Thus, TPA/PMA has been routinely used as an inducer for endogenous superoxide production.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA has a specific use in cancer diagnostics as a B-cell specific mitogen in cytogenetic testing.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] Cells must be divided in a cytogenic test to view the chromosomes.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA is used to stimulate division of B-cells during cytogenetic diagnosis of B-cell cancers such as chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA is also commonly used together with ionomycin to stimulate T-cell activation, proliferation, and cytokine production, and is used in protocols for intracellular staining of these cytokines.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA induces KSHV reactivation in PEL cell cultures via stimulation of the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK)/extracellular signal-regulated kinase (ERK) pathway.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] The pathway involves the activation of the early-immediate viral protein RTA that contributes to the activation of the lytic cycle.
[src:dauricine/12-o-tetradecanoylphorbol-13-acetate] TPA was first found in the Croton plant, a shrub found in Southeast Asia, exposure to which provokes a poison ivy-like rash.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] As of January 2017, Catalyst and another US company, Jacobus Pharmaceutical, which had been manufacturing and giving it away for free since the 1990s, were both seeking FDA approval for their iterations and marketing rights.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine phosphate (Firdapse) has orphan drug status in the EU for Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome and Catalyst holds both an orphan designation and a breakthrough therapy designation in the US.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2019, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved amifampridine tablets under the brand name **Ruzurgi** for the treatment of Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome (LEMS) in people 6 to less than 17 years of age.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Ruzurgi is no longer available in the United States.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] As of November 2018, the only other treatment approved by the FDA for LEMS (Firdapse) was only approved for use in adults.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2022, Firdapse approval was expanded to include pediatric patients 6 years of age or older.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2024, the FDA approved a supplemental New Drug Application increasing the maximum daily dose of Firdapse (amifampridine) for adults and pediatric patients weighing more than 45 kg from 80 mg to 100 mg.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is used to treat many of the congenital myasthenic syndromes, particularly those with defects in choline acetyltransferase, downstream kinase 7, and those where any kind of defect causes "fast channel" behaviour of the acetylcholine receptor.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is also used to treat symptoms of Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Because it affects voltage-gated ion channels in the heart, it is contraindicated in people with long QT syndrome and in people taking a drug that might prolong QT time like sultopride, disopyramide, cisapride, domperidone, rifampicin or ketoconazol.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is also contraindicated in people with epilepsy or badly controlled asthma.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The dose-limiting side effects include tingling or numbness, difficulty sleeping, fatigue, and loss of muscle strength.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Seizures have been observed in patients without a history of seizures.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The combination of amifampridine with pharmaceuticals that prolong QT time increases the risk of ventricular tachycardia, especially torsade de pointes; and combination with drugs that lower the seizure threshold increases the risk of seizures.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Interactions via the liver's cytochrome P450 enzyme system are considered unlikely.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome, acetylcholine release is inhibited as antibodies involved in the host response against certain cancers cross-react with Ca2+ channels on the prejunctional membrane.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine works by blocking potassium channel efflux in nerve terminals so that action potential duration is increased.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Ca2+ channels can then be open for a longer time and allow greater acetylcholine release to stimulate muscle at the end plate.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is quickly and almost completely (93–100%) absorbed from the gut.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In a study with 91 healthy subjects, maximum amifampridine concentrations in blood plasma were reached after 0.6 (±0.25) hours when taken without food, or after 1.3 (±0.9) hours after a fatty meal, meaning that the speed of absorption varies widely.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Biological half-life (2.5±0.7 hrs) and the area under the curve (AUC = 117±77 ng∙h/ml) also vary widely between subjects, but are nearly independent of food intake.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The substance is deactivated by acetylation via N-acetyltransferases to the single metabolite 3-*N*-acetylamifampridine.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Activity of these enzymes (primarily N-acetyltransferase 2) in different individuals seems to be primarily responsible for the mentioned differences in half-life and AUC: the latter is increased up to 9-fold in slow metabolizers as compared to fast metabolizers.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine is eliminated via the kidneys and urine to 74–81% as *N*-acetylamifampridine and to 19% in unchanged form.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] 3,4-Diaminopyridine is yellow solid, although commercial samples often appear brownish.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] It is readily soluble in alcohols and hot water, but only slightly in diethyl ether.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Solubility in water at 20 °C (68 °F) is 25 g/L.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The drug formulation amifampridine phosphate contains the phosphate salt, more specifically 4-aminopyridine-3-ylammonium dihydrogen phosphate.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] This salt forms prismatic, monoclinic crystals (space group C2/c) and is readily soluble in water.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The phosphate salt is stable, and does not require refrigeration.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The development of amifampridine and its phosphate has brought attention to orphan drug policies that grant market exclusivity as an incentive for companies to develop therapies for conditions that affect small numbers of people.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine, also called 3,4-DAP, was discovered in Scotland in the 1970s, and doctors in Sweden first showed its use in LEMS in the 1980s.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In the 1990s, doctors in the US, on behalf of Muscular Dystrophy Association, approached a small family-owned manufacturer of active pharmaceutical ingredients in New Jersey, Jacobus Pharmaceuticals, about manufacturing amifampridine so they could test it in clinical trials.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Jacobus elected to give the drug away to this subset of LEMS patients, and did so for about twenty years.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Doctors at the Assistance Publique – Hôpitaux de Paris had created a phosphate salt of 3,4-DAP (3,4-DAPP), and obtained an orphan designation for it in Europe in 2002.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The hospital licensed the intellectual property on the phosphate form to the French biopharma company OPI, which was acquired by EUSA Pharma in 2007, and the orphan application was transferred to EUSA in 2008.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2008 EUSA submitted an application for approval to market the phosphate form to the European Medicines Agency under the brand name Zenas.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] EUSA, through a vehicle called Huxley Pharmaceuticals, sold the rights to 3,4-DAPP to BioMarin in 2009, the same year that 3,4-DAPP was approved in Europe under the new name Firdapse.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The licensing of Firdapse in 2010 in Europe led to a sharp increase in price for the drug.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In some cases, this has led to hospitals using an unlicensed form rather than the licensed agent, as the price difference proved prohibitive.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] BioMarin has been criticized for licensing the drug on the basis of previously conducted research, and yet charging exorbitantly for it.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] A group of UK neurologists and pediatricians petitioned to prime minister David Cameron in an open letter to review the situation.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Meanwhile, in Europe, a task force of neurologists had recommended 3,4-DAP as the firstline treatment for LEMS symptoms in 2006, even though there was no approved form for marketing; it was being supplied *ad hoc*.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In 2007 the drug's international nonproprietary name was published by the WHO.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2012, while BioMarin had a Phase III trial ongoing in the US, it licensed the US rights to 3,4-DAPP, including the orphan designation and the ongoing trial, to Catalyst Pharmaceuticals.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst anticipated that it could earn $300 to $900 million per year in sales at peak sales for treatment of people with LEMS and other indications, and analysts anticipated the drug would be priced at around. $100,000 in the US.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst went on to obtain a breakthrough therapy designation for 3,4-DAPP in LEMS in 2013, an orphan designation for congenital myasthenic syndromes in 2015 and an orphan designation for myasthenia gravis in 2016.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In August 2013, analysts anticipated that FDA approval would be granted to Catalyst in LEMS by 2015.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2014, Catalyst began making available under an expanded access program.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In March 2015, Catalyst obtained an orphan designation for the use of 3,4-DAPP to treat of congenital myasthenic syndrome.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In April 2015, Jacobus presented clinical trial results with 3,4-DAP at a scientific meeting.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In December 2015, Catalyst submitted its new drug application to the FDA, and in February 2016 the FDA refused to accept it, on the basis that it wasn't complete.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In April 2016 the FDA told Catalyst it would have to gather further data.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Catalyst cut 30% of its workforce, mainly from the commercial team it was building to support an approved product, to save money to conduct the trials.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In March 2018 the company re-submitted its NDA.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The FDA approved amifampridine for the treatment of adults with Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome on November 29, 2018.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In February 2019, US Senator Bernie Sanders questioned the high price ($375,000) charged by Catalyst Pharmaceuticals for Firdapse.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2019, the privately held US company Jacobus Pharmaceutical, Princeton, New Jersey gained approval by the FDA for amifampridine tablets (*Ruzurgi*) for the treatment of LEMS in patients 6 to less than 17 years of age.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] This is the first FDA approval of a treatment specifically for pediatric patients with LEMS.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] *Firdapse* is only approved for use in adults.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Although *Ruzurgi* has been approved for pediatric patients, this approval makes it possible for adults with LEMS to get the drug off-label.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Jacobus Pharmaceutical had been manufacturing and giving it away for free since the 1990s.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The FDA decision dropped the stock of Catalyst Pharmaceuticals.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] The company's stock price has dropped about 50%.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] On January 28, 2022, in Catalyst Pharmaceuticals, Inc. v.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Becerra, the Eleventh Circuit upheld orphan exclusivity for Catalyst Pharmaceuticals and its drug Firdapse.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] With this decision, the Eleventh Circuit rejected the FDA's interpretation of orphan exclusivity and concluded that the agency had improperly approved a competitor product from Jacobus Pharmaceutical.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In October 2022, Firdapse approval was expanded to include pediatric patients 6 years of age or older.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] In May 2024, the FDA approved a supplemental New Drug Application increasing the indicated maximum daily dose of Firdapse (amifampridine) for adults and pediatric patients weighing more than 45 kg from 80 mg to 100 mg.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Amifampridine has also been proposed for the treatment of multiple sclerosis (MS).
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] A 2002 Cochrane systematic review found that there was no unbiased data to support its use for treating MS.
[src:dauricine/3-4-diaminopyridine] Isomazole is a drug that is made from an amifampridine precursor.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] In the laboratory, 4-AP is a useful pharmacological tool in studying various potassium conductances in physiology and biophysics.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] It is a relatively selective blocker of members of Kv1 (Shaker, KCNA) family of voltage-activated K+ channels.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] However, 4-AP has been shown to potentiate voltage-gated Ca2+ channel currents independent of effects on voltage-activated K+ channels.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is a potent convulsant and is used to generate seizures in animal models for the evaluation of antiseizure agents.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is also used under the trade name Avitrol as 0.5% or 1% in bird control bait.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] It causes convulsions and, infrequently, death, depending on dosage.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The manufacturer says the proper dose should cause epileptic-like convulsions which cause the poisoned birds to emit distress calls resulting in the flock leaving the site; if the dose was sub-lethal, the birds will recover after 4 or more hours without long-term ill effect.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The amount of bait should be limited so that relatively few birds are poisoned, causing the remainder of the flock to be frightened away with a minimum of mortality.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] A lethal dose will usually cause death within an hour.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The use of 4-aminopyridine in bird control has been criticized by the Humane Society of the United States.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Fampridine has been used clinically in Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome and multiple sclerosis.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] It acts by blocking voltage-gated potassium channels, prolonging action potentials and thereby increasing neurotransmitter release at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The drug has been shown to reverse saxitoxin and tetrodotoxin toxicity in tissue and animal experiments.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] In calcium entry blocker overdose in humans, 4-aminopyridine can increase the cytosolic Ca2+ concentration very efficiently independent of the calcium channels.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Fampridine has been shown to improve visual function and motor skills and relieve fatigue in patients with multiple sclerosis (MS).
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] However, the effect of the drug is strongly established for walking capacity only.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Common side effects include dizziness, nervousness and nausea, and the incidence of adverse effects was shown to be less than 5% in all studies.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP works as a potassium channel blocker.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Strong potassium currents decrease action potential duration and amplitude, which increases the probability of conduction failure − a well documented characteristic of demyelinated axons.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Potassium channel blockade has the effect of increasing axonal action potential propagation and improving the probability of synaptic vesicle release.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] A study has shown that 4-AP is a potent calcium channel activator and can improve synaptic and neuromuscular function by directly acting on the calcium channel beta subunit.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] MS patients treated with 4-AP exhibited a response rate of 29.5% to 80%.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] A long-term study (32 months) indicated that 80-90% of patients who initially responded to 4-AP exhibited long-term benefits.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Although improving symptoms, 4-AP does not inhibit progression of MS.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Another study, conducted in Brazil, showed that treatment based on fampridine was considered efficient in 70% of the patients.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Spinal cord injury patients have also seen improvement with 4-AP therapy.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] These improvements include sensory, motor and pulmonary function, with a decrease in spasticity and pain.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-Aminopyridine is a gene-targeted therapy option for KCNA2-related disorders with a gain-of-function (GOF) or some mix-of-function (MOF) gene mutations.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] It has shown to improve seizure control, gait, ataxia, alertness, and cognition.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] GOF KCNA2 disorders are caused by voltage-gated potassium channels in the central nervous system that stay open and allow too much flow of potassium currents.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Some MOF KCNA2 disorders also act like GOF in regards to their flow of potassium through the channel which is why they may also benefit from 4-AP therapy.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP acts by closing these channels and improves the natural flow of potassium through the neuron.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] As of 2025 the use of 4-AP for KCNA2 is in an experimental stage, but it has shown significant improvement for most patients that have used it.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Out of 13 documented patients, eight became seizure free, two others experienced a reduction in seizures, and 11 had improved gait, ataxia, alertness, cognition, or speech.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Only one patient experienced side effects of increased seizures and no other symptoms were reported.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Authors of the first 4-AP KCNA2 study created an online tool to guide physicians in identifying which KCNA2 patients would benefit from this therapy.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] It is publicly accessible due to the importance for treating this disease from young age.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] See the article for details on accessing this information.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Clinical studies have shown that 4-AP is capable of reversing the effects of tetrodotoxin poisoning in animals, however, its effectiveness as an antidote in humans has not yet been determined.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Case reports have shown that overdoses with 4-AP can lead to paresthesias, seizures, and atrial fibrillation.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-aminopyridine is excreted by the kidneys.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] 4-AP should not be given to people with significant kidney disease (e.g., acute kidney injury or advanced chronic kidney disease) due to the higher risk of seizures with increased circulating levels of 4-AP.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The drug was originally intended, by Acorda Therapeutics, to have the brand name *Amaya*, however the name was changed to *Ampyra* to avoid potential confusion with other marketed pharmaceuticals.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Four of Acorda's patents pertaining to Ampyra were invalidated in 2017 by the United States District Court for the District of Delaware and a fifth patent expired in 2018.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Since then, generic alternatives have been developed for the U.S. market.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] The drug is marketed by Biogen Idec in Canada as *Fampyra* and as *Dalstep* in India by Sun Pharma.
[src:dauricine/4-aminopyridine] Dalfampridine completed Phase II clinical trials for Parkinson's disease in July 2014.
[src:dauricine/4-methylpregabalin] However these drugs are still of relatively low potency, and scientists have struggled for years to come up with an improvement on pregabalin, with increasing pressure to find a suitably improved replacement before the patent on pregabalin expired in 2018.
[src:dauricine/4-methylpregabalin] Eventually it was discovered that pregabalin is actively transported across the blood–brain barrier by the system L neutral amino acid transporter protein, which usually functions to transport certain amino acids, including leucine, valine and isoleucine, into the brain.
[src:dauricine/4-methylpregabalin] However, after extensive searching it was discovered that one enantiomer of the relatively simple derivative 4-methylpregabalin, was both 4× higher in binding affinity to α2δ channels than pregabalin, and also retained similar affinity for the system L transporter.
[src:dauricine/4-methylpregabalin] This was tested in animals and as hoped, was found to have similar effectiveness to pregabalin as an analgesic and with around 2–3× the potency.
[src:dauricine/4-methylpregabalin] It remains unclear at this stage whether (3*R*,4*R*)-4-methylpregabalin will now be further developed for medical use in humans however, given the recent development of several competing drugs from the same family which are much further advanced in clinical trials.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] AH-1058 displays characteristics of Class IV antiarrhythmics (L-type calcium channel blockers).
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Class I antiarrhythmic (sodium channel blocker) characteristics have also been seen, but the effect AH-1058 has on sodium channels is variable and unknown.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Some proposed uses for AH-1058 include the treatment of angina pectoris, stenosis of the outflow tract from obstructive hypertrophic cardiomyopathy and ventricular arrhythmias.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Treatment of these conditions (long term and short term) is possible due to the cardioselective nature of AH-1058 and the ability of AH-1058 to inhibit calcium channels and thus reduce cardiac contractility and energy consumption.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Studies have compared AH-1058 to widely used and clinically available drugs such as verapamil (a Class IV antiarrhythmic drug) and atenolol (a beta blocker) to assess the efficacy of AH-1058.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] The effects of AH-1058 are slower to onset but longer-lasting than those of verapamil and atenolol.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] In addition, the minimal effects AH-1058 has on total peripheral vascular resistance is an important advantage over atenolol and verapamil, as these drugs can be taken long term for disease management.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Lastly AH-1058 displays a greater selectivity for cardiac tissue over verapamil and atenolol with the same level of potency as verapamil in vitro.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] AH-1058 studies have been limited to in vitro and in vivo canine and guinea-pig models, with a greater potency displayed in vitro than in vivo.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] Along with decreased potency in vivo, blood levels do not correlate with AH-1058 activity.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] AH-1058 is a cardioselective L-type calcium channel blocker.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] AH-1058 binds to the same sites on the alpha-1 subunit of L-type calcium channels as phenylalkylamines (ex. verapamil) and benzothiazepines; both of which are well known calcium channel blockers.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] These sites on the alpha-1 subunit differ from the active site of the calcium channel, meaning AH-1058 binds L-type calcium channels allosterically to alter activity.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] In addition AH-1058 appears to interact with multiple states of L-type calcium channels (i.e. resting and inactive) to suppress calcium currents.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] A minor effect on sodium channels at higher concentrations has also been seen, but these effects appear to vary between species.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] The calcium blocking activity of AH-1058 can decrease ventricular contractility, heart rate, and conductance through the atrioventricular node.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] In addition AH-1058 has been shown to decrease systolic blood pressure while minimally affecting total peripheral vascular resistance and leaving diastolic blood pressure unaffected.
[src:dauricine/ah-1058] The order of the potency of the effects AH-1058 has on the cardiovascular system is: ventricular contraction > coronary blood flow >> atrioventricular conduction > sinoatrial automaticity (level of sinoatrial self-activation).
